are-imbolnavit-covid-19-varsta-medie-pacientilor-41-ani.htm |title=INFOGRAFIC Ce v\u00e2rste au rom\u00e2nii care s-au \u00eemboln\u0103vit de COVID-19. V\u00e2rsta medie a pacien\u021bilor - 41 de ani |last=H., I. |date=18 March 2020 |website=HotNews.ro}}</ref>\n\n== Response by sector ==\n=== Economics ===\n[[File:Emergency measures COVID 19 Romania.jpg|thumb|200px|\"Please  keep your distance\" notice in a Bucharest supermarket, 28 March 2020.]]\n[[File:Carrefour Brasov shelves, Covid.jpg|thumb|200px|Flour almost sold out, Bra\u0219ov, 14 March]]  \nDuring the second week of March, the [[Bucharest Stock Exchange]] recorded losses on all five trading sessions, the main index BET collapsing with 17.6%, the steepest decline since December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.zf.ro/burse-fonduri-mutuale/saptamana-de-cosmar-pentru-bursa-romaneasca-prabusire-de-17-6-inca-nu-stim-daca-socul-economic-va-dura-1-luna-2-luni-sau-mai-mult-18982027 |title=S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2na de co\u0219mar pentru bursa rom\u00e2neasc\u0103: pr\u0103bu\u0219ire de 17,6%. \"\u00cenc\u0103 nu \u0219tim dac\u0103 \u0219ocul economic va dura 1 lun\u0103, 2 luni, sau mai mult\" |last=Popescu, Liviu |date=14 March 2020 |website=Ziarul Financiar}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the [[National Bank of Romania]] announced a reference rate of 4.8242 [[Romanian leu|lei]]/[[euro]], a historical maximum for the single European currency against the leu.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://incont.stirileprotv.ro/cursuri/moneda-unica-marcheaza-un-nou-maxim-istoric-in-raport-cu-leul-c-curs-a-anuntat-bnr-pentru-euro.html |title=Moneda unic\u0103 marcheaz\u0103 un nou maxim istoric \u00een raport cu leul. Ce curs a anun\u021bat BNR pentru euro |date=16 March 2020 |website=inCont.ro}}</ref> The leu continued its depreciation, reaching a maximum of 4.8448 lei/euro on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economica.net/curs-bnr-azi-17-martie-2020-leu-euro-dolar-franc-elvetian-curs-valutar-interbancar-robor-aur_181227.html |title=A doua zi consecutiv\u0103 \u00een care leul atinge minimul istoric \u00een fa\u021ba euro. Curs BNR 17.03.2020: 4,8448 lei/euro |date=17 March 2020 |website=Economica.net}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn March 9, interim Prime-minister [[Ludovic Orban]] announced the closure of all schools between March 11 and 22. The measure targeted all kindergartens, primary, secondary and high schools in Romania, both public and private, according to Education Minister {{ill|Monica Anisie|ro}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.romania-insider.com/romania-closes-schools-coronavirus-march-2020 |title=Update: Romania closes all schools to fight coronavirus outbreak |date=9 March 2020 |website=Romania-Insider.com}}</ref> The decision affects 3.5 million students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/bucurestenii-inchiderea-scolilor-coronavirus-2909216 |title=Cum se adapteaz\u0103 bucure\u0219tenii la \u00eenchiderea \u0219colilor \u0219i ce p\u0103rere au despre \u00eenmul\u021birea cazurilor de coronavirus |last=Stanciu |first=Daniel |last2=Nistor |first2=Cosmin |date=11 March 2020 |website=Libertatea |last3=Capoeanu |first3=George}}</ref> Likewise, several universities in the major student centres suspended their courses. These include the [[University of Bucharest]], the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]], the [[Politehnica University of Bucharest]], the [[Babe\u0219-Bolyai University]], the [[West University of Timi\u0219oara]], etc.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/universitatea-bucuresti-isi-suspenda-cursurile-2908415 |title=UPDATE. Universitatea din Bucure\u0219ti \u0219i ASE \u00ee\u0219i suspend\u0103 cursurile p\u00e2n\u0103 la sf\u00e2r\u0219itul lunii |last=Radu, Cristina |date=11 March 2020 |website=Libertatea}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediafax.ro/coronavirus/cea-mai-mare-universitate-din-tara-ubb-suspenda-cursurile-pana-in-22-martie-18959559 |title=Cea mai mare universitate din \u021bar\u0103, UBB, suspend\u0103 cursurile p\u00e2n\u0103 \u00een 22 martie |last=M\u0103gr\u0103dean, Vasile |date=10 March 2020 |website=Mediafax}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pressalert.ro/2020/03/se-suspenda-cursurile-si-la-universitatea-de-vest-din-timisoara-din-cauza-coronavirus/ |title=Se suspend\u0103 cursurile \u0219i la Universitatea de Vest din Timi\u0219oara, din cauza COVID 19 |last=M\u00ee\u021b, Adriana |date=11 March 2020 |website=pressalert.ro}}</ref> Furthermore, Anisie announced that, as a measure of prevention and control of the illnesses with COVID-19 in schools, the Ministry of Education had decided to suspend all county and regional school olympiads, as well as sports competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agerpres.ro/educatie-stiinta/2020/03/09/mec-olimpiadele-scolare-judetene-si-regionale-precum-si-concursurile-sportive-suspendate--462247 |title=MEC: Olimpiadele \u015fcolare jude\u0163ene \u015fi regionale, precum \u015fi concursurile sportive - suspendate |last=AGERPRES |website=www.agerpres.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe show ''Tele\u0219coal\u0103'' (Teleschool), announced by the Ministry of Education and dedicated to the students who stay at home during the period when the schools are closed, started on [[TVR 2]] on March 16, at 9 a.m. Students can follow, from Monday to Friday, [[mathematics]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[biology]], [[history]] and [[geography]] classes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mbl.hotnews.ro/stire/23718809 |title=TVR: Tele\u0219coala pentru elevii care stau acas\u0103 \u00eencepe pe 16 martie - Hotnews Mobile |website=mbl.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.hotnews.ro/stire/23727012 |title=Tele\u0218coala a fost LIVE VIDEO pe ecrane \u0219i pe site-ul TVR+. ORARUL complet al cursurilor din prima s\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2n\u0103 - Hotnews Mobile |website=mobile.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Anisie announced that schools would remain closed while the state of emergency was in place, at least until after the [[Easter]] holidays.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/educatie/ministrul-educatiei-scolile-raman-inchise-pana-dupa-paste-cat-e-anuntata-starea-de-urgenta-1276054 |title=Ministrul Educa\u021biei: \u0218colile r\u0103m\u00e2n \u00eenchise p\u00e2n\u0103 dup\u0103 Pa\u0219te, c\u00e2t e anun\u021bat\u0103 starea de urgen\u021b\u0103 |website=www.digi24.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mbl.hotnews.ro/stire/23726531 |title=Monica Anisie, ministrul Educa\u021biei: \u0218colile r\u0103m\u00e2n \u00eenchise p\u00e2n\u0103 dup\u0103 Pa\u0219te, c\u00e2t e anun\u021bat\u0103 starea de urgen\u021b\u0103 - Hotnews Mobile |website=mbl.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\nOn April 1, in response to a [[fake news]] story which had gained traction on [[social media]] and was being destributed on [[WhatsApp]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://m.ziare.com/scoala/ministerul-educatiei-dezminte-un-fake-news-care-circula-pe-whatsapp-cursurile-nu-se-reiau-pe-6-aprilie-vom-face-denunt-penal-1604511 |title=Ministerul Educatiei dezminte un fake news, care circula pe Whatsapp: Cursurile nu se reiau pe 6 aprilie! Vom face denunt penal |work=Ziare.com |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.romaniatv.net/scoli-inchise-pana-pe-6-aprilie-fake-news-in-mediul-online-ministerul-educatiei-precizari-de-ulti_515528.html |title=\u015eCOLI \u00ceNCHISE p\u00e2n\u0103 pe 6 aprilie, FAKE NEWS \u00een mediul online. Ministerul Educa\u0163iei, preciz\u0103ri de ultim\u0103 or\u0103 |date=2020-04-01 |website=romaniatv.net |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>, saying that students would have to return to school in less than a week, Anisie and the Ministry of Education issued an official statement condemning the spread of false information and promised to provide in the next few days the date for the re-opening of schools, as well as the national examinations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/document-fals-cu-privire-la-modificarea-structurii-anului-scolar-2019-2020-distribuit-online-reactia-ministerului-educatiei-1284871 |title=Document fals cu privire la modificarea structurii anului \u0219colar 2019-2020, distribuit online. Reac\u021bia Ministerului Educa\u021biei |website=www.digi24.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/ministerul-educatiei-demonteaza-un-fake-news-care-circula-online-cursurile-nu-se-reiau-pe-6-aprilie-vom-face-denunt-penal-2936604 |title=Ministerul Educa\u0163iei demonteaz\u0103 un fake news care circul\u0103 online: \"Cursurile nu se reiau pe 6 aprilie. Vom face denun\u0163 penal\" |date=2020-04-01 |website=Libertatea |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.realitatea.net/stiri/actual/ministerul-educatiei-demonteaza-un-fake-news-ce-se-intampla-cu-anul-scolar_5e7fcda91773ac0fd00c0fa2 |title=Ministerul Educa\u021biei demonteaz\u0103 un fake news: Ce se \u00eent\u00e2mpl\u0103 cu anul \u0219colar |website=REALITATEA.NET |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\nThe [[Romanian Football Federation]] and the [[Romanian Handball Federation]] decided to suspend all matches until March 31.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digisport.ro/fotbal/pandemia-de-coronavirus-a-pus-lacat-pe-fotbalul-romanesc-frf-a-suspendat-toate-meciurile-810522 |title=Pandemia de coronavirus a pus \"lac\u0103t\" pe fotbalul rom\u00e2nesc! FRF a suspendat toate meciurile |date=12 March 2020 |website=Digi Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://realitateasportiva.net/frh-anunta-ca-toate-competitiile-pe-plan-intern-au-fost-suspendate/ |title=FRH anun\u021b\u0103 c\u0103 toate competi\u021biile pe plan intern au fost suspendate |last=Bulgakov, Kadi |date=13 March 2020 |website=Realitatea Sportiv\u0103}}</ref> The rugby match between Romania and Belgium, to be held in [[Boto\u0219ani]] on March 14, was postponed by [[Rugby Europe]].<ref name=\"ziare\" /> The [[IWF Junior World Weightlifting Championships]] in [[Bucharest]], scheduled for March 14\u201321, have been cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://realitateasportiva.net/o-competitie-sportiva-din-romania-anulata-din-cauza-epidemiei-de-coronavirus/ |title=O competi\u021bie sportiv\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia, anulat\u0103 din cauza epidemiei de coronavirus |last=Iona\u0219cu, Andrei |date=2 March 2020 |website=Realitatea Sportiv\u0103}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Romania}}\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries Confirmed cases and deaths by country, territory, or conveyance] (worldometer)\n* [https://instnsp.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/5eced796595b4ee585bcdba03e30c127 Interactive map with confirmed cases, people in quarantine, isolated people, etc.] (ArcGIS)\n* [https://covid19.geo-spatial.org/dashboard/main Maps and statistics on the situation of COVID-19 pandemic in Romania] (geo-spatial.org)\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Romania|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Romania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Romania]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 in Romania]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Romania]]\n", "name_user": "CaptainFugu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 4\u2013present: Surgical masks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Romania"}
{"title_page": "Whitney Cummings", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedian and actress}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Whitney Cummings\n| image =  \n| image_size =\n| caption = Cummings in 2019\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|09|04}}\n| birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| medium = Stand-up, television, film\n| active = 2004\u2013present\n| height        = 1.78 m\n| genre = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Observational comedy]]<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Atlantic]]|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/the-triumph-of-soap-box-comedy/427104/|title=The Triumph of Soap-Box Comedy|last=Garber|first=Megan|date=January 26, 2016|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[insult comedy]]\n* [[blue comedy]]\n}}\n| subject = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Gender differences]]\n* [[sexism]]\n* [[human sexuality]]\n* [[Intimate relationship|relationships]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.whitneycummings.com/}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n}}\n\n'''Whitney Cummings''' (born September 4, 1982) is an American [[stand-up comedy|stand-up comedian]], actress, producer, writer, director, and podcaster. Her credits include one comedy album, four stand-up specials, three ''[[Comedy Central Roast]]s'', and numerous television series in which she has served various roles including producer, director, showrunner, and actress.\n\nA native of [[Washington, D.C.]], Cummings pursued a comedy career in [[Los Angeles]] after graduating from the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where she had studied with the intention of becoming a journalist. After beginning standup in 2004, she secured regular appearances as a roundtable guest on ''[[Chelsea Lately]]''. She subsequently created, produced, and starred in [[NBC]]'s ''[[Whitney (TV series)|Whitney]]'', a sitcom in which she portrayed a semi-fictionalized version of herself. The series ran for two seasons before being cancelled in 2013. Simultaneously, Cummings created the [[CBS]] sitcom ''[[2 Broke Girls]]'', which also began in 2011, and concluded in 2017.\n\nCummings released her first hour-long standup special, ''Money Shot'', in 2010 on [[Comedy Central]]. She followed this with a second standup special for the network, entitled ''I Love You'' (2014). Her third special, ''I'm Your Girlfriend'', was released on [[HBO]] in 2016. Beginning in 2018, Cummings served as a producer and writer for the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] revival of ''[[Roseanne]]'', but left the project prior to its cancellation. Cummings' fourth special, ''Can I Touch It?'', premiered on [[Netflix]] in July 2019.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life===\nCummings was born on September 4, 1982,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.etonline.com/slideshow/gallery/117647_Thirty_Flirty_Celebs_Who_Are_Turning_30_This_Year/47109 |title=Thirty & Flirty: Celebs Who Are Turning 30 This Year: Whitney Cummings |date=2012 |work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |publisher=CBS Studios |location=New York City, New York |access-date=October 20, 2018|archivedate= October 21, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181021124745/https://www.etonline.com/slideshow/gallery/117647_Thirty_Flirty_Celebs_Who_Are_Turning_30_This_Year/47109|url-status=live|quote=Whitney Cummings -- September 4, 1982}}</ref> in [[Washington, D.C.]],<ref name=Vanity-Fair>{{cite news|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/01/whitney-cummings-hbo-special|title=Whitney Cummings Got Hooked on Tinder for Her HBO Special|date=January 21, 2016|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=May 11, 2018|last=Miller, Julie}}</ref><ref name=WashingtonPost-Brazen-2010>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/08/AR2010120806415.html|title=Comedian Whitney Cummings: Bewitching, brazen and with jokes to make you blush|last=Zak|first=Dan|date=December 8, 2010|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> the youngest of three children in a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] family.<ref name=Vanity-Fair/> She has an older half-brother named Kevin and an older sister named Ashley.<ref name=Vulture-Respect-2012/><ref name=WashingtonPost-Brazen-2010/> Her mother, Patti Cummings, a native of [[Texas]],<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|location=Houston, Texas|title=Comedian Whitney Cummings sparks social media outrage over small Texas town's legal tradition|last=Gill|first=Julian|date=April 17, 2019|url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Owner-of-Texas-hog-baying-competition-fires-back-13774588.php|archive-url=http://archive.is/wip/SbKvw|archive-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> is a former public relations director of [[Neiman Marcus]] at [[Mazza Gallerie]].<ref name=WashingtonPost-ReliableSource-2004>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/623413831.html?dids=623413831:623413831&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+25%2C+2004&author=Richard+Leiby&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=The+Reliable+Source&pqatl=google|title=The Reliable Source|last=Leiby|first=Richard|date=April 25, 2004|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Vulture-Respect-2012>{{cite news|last1=Grigoriadis|first1=Vanessa|title=Can Whitney Cummings Get Some Respect?|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/11/whitney-cummings-on-love-you-mean-it.html|accessdate=August 17, 2014|publisher=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture.com]]|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=November 18, 2012}}</ref><ref name=WashingtonPost-Brazen-2010/> Her parents divorced when she was five years old.<ref name=WashingtonPost-Brazen-2010/><ref name=TVGuide-HowDifferent-2011>{{cite news|last1=Stanhope|first1=Kate|title=Whitney: How Different Is Whitney Cummings From Her TV Persona, Really?|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/whitney-cummings-interview-1037134.aspx|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[TV Guide]]|date=September 9, 2011}}</ref><ref name=LasVegasWeekly-Int-2013>{{cite news|last1=Duck|first1=Allison|title=The Weekly Interview: Whitney Cummings|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/ae/2013/apr/24/weekly-interview-comedian-whitney-cummings|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[Las Vegas Weekly]]|date=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe has stated that she was raised in a dysfunctional, [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] household, and that her mother struggled to support their family.<ref name=scariest>{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/jan/12/whitney-cummings-stand-up-comedy-female-brain|title=Whitney Cummings: 'The scariest place to perform standup is America'|last=Czajkowski|first=Elise|date=January 12, 2017|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> At age twelve, she temporarily resided with her aunt in [[Virginia]].<ref name=Vanity-Fair/> Cummings attended [[St. Andrew's Episcopal School (Maryland)|St. Andrew's Episcopal School]] in [[Potomac, Maryland]], graduating in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saes.org/news/detail.aspx?pageaction=ViewSinglePublic&LinkID=5259&ModuleID=7|title=Whitney Cummings '00 Making Her Mark in Entertainment World|date=April 23, 2010|publisher=St. Andrew's Episcopal School|accessdate=November 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102194746/http://www.saes.org/news/detail.aspx?pageaction=ViewSinglePublic&LinkID=5259&ModuleID=7|archivedate=January 2, 2014}}</ref> During high school, she interned at Washington's NBC-owned television station [[WRC-TV]].<ref name=WashingtonPost-Brazen-2010/><ref name=AmericasComedy-FullMonty-2011>{{cite web|url=http://americascomedy.com/a-womans-mind-full-monty-whitney-cummings|title=A Woman\u2019s Mind Full Monty \u2014 Whitney Cummings|publisher=AmericasComedy.com|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=September 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=JesterJournal-Interview-2011>{{cite web|url=http://www.jesterjournal.com/intwcummings.htm|title=The Jester Interview: Whitney Cummings|publisher=Jester.com|date=June 6, 2011|accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref> She studied acting at Washington, D.C.'s Studio Theater.<ref name=Variety-10Comics-2007>{{cite news|last1=Frankel|first1=Daniel|title=Whitney Cummings: 10 Comics to Watch|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/features/whitney-cummings-2-1117960261/|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 27, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter high school, Cummings enrolled at the [[Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania|Annenberg School for Communication]] at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. To pay her tuition, she worked as a department store [[model (person)|model]] at local shopping malls.<ref name=\"Vanity-Fair\"/> She graduated ''[[magna cum laude]]'' in 2004 with a degree in Communications,<ref name=AmericasComedy-FullMonty-2011 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/current/2011-05-05/numbers/penn-entertainers|title=Penn Entertainers|last=Johnson|first=Greg|date=May 5, 2011|work=Penn Current|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> and initially aspired for a career as a journalist.<ref name=reporter>{{cite web|work=[[New York Daily News]]|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/confidential/whitney-news-bad-article-1.1898301|title=Whitney Cummings almost became a reporter before finding comedy to over come the facts of an abusive, sad and lonely childhood|date=August 10, 2014|access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132010: Career beginnings===\nCummings moved to [[Los Angeles]] after college and worked on ''[[Punk'd]]'' on [[MTV]] in 2004.<ref name=WashingtonPost-ReliableSource-2004/> That same year, she starred in the low-budget thriller ''EMR'', which was screened at [[Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]].<ref name=Variety-EMR-2005>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117926258?refcatid=31|title=Review: \u2018EMR\u2019|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|date=February 17, 2005|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=TVGuide-Punkd-2004>{{cite news|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/whitney-cummings-ashton-41073.aspx|last=Katner|first=Ben|title=Whitney Rocks Punk'd!|date=June 11, 2004|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> Cummings began performing stand-up in 2004.<ref name=lb>{{cite web|url=https://thelaughbutton.com/features/whitney-cummings-wants-girlfriend/|work=The Laugh Button|title=Whitney Cummings wants to be your girlfriend|date=January 22, 2016|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' named her one of 10 Comics to Watch in 2007.<ref name=Variety-10Comics-2007/> In 2008, she appeared in the San Francisco audition for ''[[Last Comic Standing]]'', although she did not pass the showcase.<ref name=lb/>\n\nShe co-starred on ''[[The Tony Rock Project]]'' and appeared in the 2008 romantic comedy ''[[Made of Honor]]''. Beginning in 2007, Cummings appeared as a regular roundtable guest on the [[E!]] series ''[[Chelsea Lately]]'', and continued to appear until its conclusion in 2014. In 2008, she was named one of 12 Rising Stars of Comedy by ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref name=EW-12RisingStars-2008>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20239791_20542065,00.html#20542078|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first1=Whitney|last1=Pastorek|first2=Dan|last2=Snierson|title=12 Rising Stars of Comedy|date=November 13, 2008}}</ref> She subsequently appeared as a comedy roaster in the ''[[Comedy Central Roast]]s'' of [[Joan Rivers]] (2009), [[David Hasselhoff]] (2010), and [[Donald Trump]] (2011).<ref name=WashingtonPost-Brazen-2010/>\n\nIn August 2010, her first one-hour special, titled ''Whitney Cummings: Money Shot'', premiered on Comedy Central. In 2010, Cummings went on tour with [[Denis Leary]] and the ''[[Rescue Me (U.S. TV series)|Rescue Me]] Comedy Tour'' to promote the show's sixth season. She also appeared with Leary on ''[[Douchebags and Donuts]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Leary: Douchebags and Donuts|date=January 16, 2011|publisher=[[Comedy Central]]|url=http://www.cc.com/episodes/gyljo1/stand-up-library-denis-leary--douchebags-and-donuts-season-1-ep-101}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u2013present: Television projects and specials, book===\n[[File: Whitney Cummings (2016).jpg|thumb|upright=.9|right|Cummings performing live in 2016]]\nIn 2011, two multi-camera, live-audience sitcoms Cummings created<ref name=HReporter-10Things-2011>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Lacey|title='Whitney': 10 Things to Know About the NBC Comedy|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/whitney-10-things-know-nbc-217704|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=August 1, 2011}}</ref> were picked up by broadcast networks: ''[[2 Broke Girls]]'' (which she co-created and executive produced with [[Michael Patrick King]]) and ''[[Whitney (TV series)|Whitney]]'' (which she starred in, executive produced, and created).<ref name=NYTimes-PinHopes-2011>{{cite news|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|title=2 Networks Pin Their Hopes on One Comedian|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/21/arts/television/whitney-cummingss-many-roles-in-whitney-and-2-for-broke.html|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 20, 2011}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-NoEscaping-2011>{{cite news|last1=Goldman|first1=Andrew|title=There Is No Escaping Whitney Cummings|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/18/magazine/there-is-no-escaping-whitney-cummings.html|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=The New York Times|date=September 16, 2011}}</ref> ''Whitney'', in which Cummings portrayed a semi-fictionalized version of herself, was not well-received by critics,<ref name=Metacritic-49>{{cite web|title=Whitney: Season 1|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/whitney|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref><ref name=USAToday-Fails-2011>{{cite news|last1=Blanco|first1=Robert|title='Whitney' sitcom fails in its delivery|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/story/2011-09-22/whitney-cummings-sitcom/50502994/1|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|date=September 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=NYorker-CrassWarfare-2011>{{cite web|last1=Nussbaum|first1=Emiy|title=Crass Warfare: Raunch and ridicule on \"Whitney\" and \"2 Broke Girls.\"|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2011/11/28/crass-warfare|work=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=August 18, 2014|date=November 28, 2011}}</ref> and Cummings acknowledges it was a learning curve for her.<ref name=HReporter-TCAs-2012>{{cite news|last1=O'Connell|first1=Michael|title=TCA 2012: Whitney Cummings Admits 'I Wish I Knew How to Act'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tca-2012-whitney-cummings-nbc-sitcom-laugh-track-354569|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=July 25, 2012}}</ref><ref name=NYMag-6-Showrunners-2012>{{cite web|last1=Adalian|first1=Josef|title=The New Girls: Six female showrunners on why TV just keeps getting better.|url=http://nymag.com/arts/tv/upfronts/2012/women-showrunners-2012-5|work=New York|accessdate=August 18, 2014|date=May 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Vulture-6Showrunner-Outtakes-2012>{{cite web|last1=Adalian|first1=Josef|title=Six Female Showrunners Talk Ratings, Their Comedy Icons, and Internet Hate|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/05/female-showrunners-talk-ratings-internet-hate.html|publisher=Vulture.com|work=New York|accessdate=August 18, 2014|date=May 25, 2012}}</ref> The series was canceled after two seasons in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/05/nbcs-parks-recreation-renewed|title=UPDATE: NBC's 'Whitney' & '1600 Penn' Cancelled, 'Parks & Recreation' Renewed|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 9, 2013|accessdate=May 9, 2013}}</ref> While still working on the second season of ''Whitney'', Cummings also hosted a talk show, ''[[Love You, Mean It with Whitney Cummings]]'', on E! in 2012,<ref name=HReporter-TalkshowGreenlit-2012>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Lacey|title=E! Greenlights a Weekly Whitney Cummings Talk Show|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/whitney-cumings-talk-show-e-weekly-317898|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=April 29, 2012}}</ref> which was cancelled after 11 episodes.<ref name=NYTimes-GoodBadNews-2013>{{cite news|last1=Kepler|first1=Adam|title=For Whitney Cummings, Good and Bad Ratings News|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/15/for-whitney-cummings-good-and-bad-ratings-news|accessdate=August 18, 2014|department=ArtsBeat|work=The New York Times|date=February 15, 2013}}</ref><ref name=HReporter-TalkshowPlugPulled-2013>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Lacey|title=E! Pulls Plug on Whitney Cummings' Late-Night Show|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/e-pulls-plug-whitney-cummings-421584|accessdate=August 18, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> Cummings later stated that she was overworking herself during this period, and was also in the midst of battling an [[eating disorder]] in which she would [[binge eating|binge eat]] followed by compulsive exercise.{{sfn|Cummings|2017|pages=122\u2013126, 154}} In June 2014, Cummings released her second hour-long special, ''I Love You'', on Comedy Central.<ref name=Vulture-Sarah-2014>{{cite web|last1=Silverman|first1=Sarah|title=Sarah Silverman Talks to Whitney Cummings About the Expectation That Comedians Need to Be in Movies|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/06/sarah-silverman-and-whitney-cummings-had-a-wonderful-in-depth-conversation-about-comedy.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827005542/https://www.vulture.com/2014/06/sarah-silverman-and-whitney-cummings-had-a-wonderful-in-depth-conversation-about-comedy.html|archive-date=August 27, 2019|date=June 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHer third hour-long special debuted on HBO in 2016, titled \"I'm Your Girlfriend\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbo.com/specials/whitney-cummings-im-your-girlfriend|title=Whitney Cummings: I'm Your Girlfriend|website=HBO|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> Reviews were mixed, suggesting it felt less comedic than her previous stand up performances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/the-triumph-of-soap-box-comedy/427104/|title=Comedy, or TED Talk?|last=Garber|first=Megan|date=2016-01-26|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nCummings had a supporting role in the 2017 thriller ''[[Unforgettable (2017 film)|Unforgettable]]'', starring [[Katherine Heigl]] and [[Rosario Dawson]], released in April 2017.<ref name=unf>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/whitney-cummings-unforgettable-audition/|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|title=Whitney Cummings Recalls Unforgettable Audition|date=April 20, 2017|author=Guglielmi, Jodi|access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> The following month,''2 Broke Girls'' was cancelled after having run six consecutive seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/2-broke-girls-canceled-cbs-after-6-seasons-1202092530/|title=\u20182 Broke Girls\u2019 Canceled By CBS After 6 Seasons|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=May 13, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=August 29, 2017}}</ref> Cummings made her directorial debut with ''[[The Female Brain (film)|The Female Brain]]'' (2017), an independent comedy film distributed by [[IFC Films]], which Cummings also starred in.<ref name=fb>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/markets-festivals/whitney-cummings-female-brain-ifc-1202614870/|title=Whitney Cummings Comedy \u2018The Female Brain\u2019 Sells to IFC (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2017, Cummings published her first book, titled ''I'm Fine...And Other Lies'', a collection of personal stories about her life.<ref>{{cite web|title=I'm Fine...And Other Lies |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/whitney-cummings/im-fineand-other-lies/ |website=kirkusreviews.com |date= |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2018, Cummings served as one of the head writers, an executive producer, and overseer of day-to-day production of the revival of the comedy series ''[[Roseanne]]'', for ABC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/04/28/roseanne-revival-may-works/101039122|title='Roseanne' revival may be in the works|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|access-date=April 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2017/04/28/roseanne-revival-abc-netflix-eight-episodes/|title=Roseanne Revival Eyed at ABC|website=TVLine|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|date=April 28, 2017|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> Cummings left the show, however, after its star, [[Roseanne Barr]], made a series of inflammatory, racially-charged jokes on her [[Twitter]] account, which subsequently resulted in the series' cancellation.<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|last=Husband|first=Andrew|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewhusband/2019/07/31/whitney-cummings-opens-up-about-her-decision-to-leave-roseanne-before-its-cancellation/#cf6132f22a7b|date=July 31, 2019|archive-url=http://archive.is/T8sXp|archive-date=August 27, 2019|title=Whitney Cummings Opens Up About Her Decision to Leave ''Roseanne'' Before Its Cancellation|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n\nHer fourth hour-long special ''Can I Touch It?'' was released on July 30, 2019 on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decider.com/2019/07/30/whitney-cummings-sex-robot-netflix-special/|title=Whitney Cummings Made a Sex Robot of Herself for \u2018Can I Touch It?\u2019 Netflix Special|date=July 30, 2019|website=Decider|language=en|access-date=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/comedian-whitney-cummings-debuts-her-own-lifelike-sex-robot/news-story/f2c856042eca1aca2d15334043ae23a6|work=[[News.com.au]]|title=Comedian Whitney Cummings debuts her own lifelike \u2018sex robot\u2019|last=Speliberg|first=Claire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814184710/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/comedian-whitney-cummings-debuts-her-own-lifelike-sex-robot/news-story/f2c856042eca1aca2d15334043ae23a6|date=July 31, 2019|archive-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2019, Cummings launched her first podcast entitled ''Good for You''.  Her first guest was actor/producer [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]].\n\n==Influences==\n[[File:Pretty Big Deal with Ashley Graham - Whitney Cummings Breaks Down Codependency.webm|thumb|Cummings discussing her perspective on comedy, influences, and approach to [[co-dependency]] in 2019]]\nCummings has described her comedic influences, beginning with [[Paul Reiser]], who she said \"made these hysterical, brilliant commentary about the most mundane things and open it up to a hysterical world.\"<ref name=Fred-TrailerPark-2008 /> Other important influences for her were [[George Carlin]], whom she says challenged her to \"question everything.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|title=9 questions for Whitney Cummings|url=https://www.vox.com/conversations/2017/4/15/15261288/9-questions-for-whitney-cummings|date=April 15, 2017|last=Illing|first=Sean|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708094757/https://www.vox.com/conversations/2017/4/15/15261288/9-questions-for-whitney-cummings|archive-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> Later influences were [[Dave Attell]] (\"a legend now but he\u2019s very edgy\"), [[Lenny Bruce]] and [[Bill Hicks]].<ref name=Fred-TrailerPark-2008>{{cite web|last1=Stipp|first1=Christopher|title=Trailer Park Whitney Cummings|url=http://asitecalledfred.com/2008/05/02/trailer-park-whitney-cummings|publisher=ASiteCalledFred.com|accessdate=August 18, 2014|date=May 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2004\n|''[[Dogwoof Pictures#Film distribution|EMR]]''\n|CyberBunnyLilly\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/emr|title=EMR|archive-url=http://archive.today/wip/B6GeU|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2006\n|''Hooked''\n|Vanessa\n|Short film\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2006\n|''Life is Short''\n|Natalie\n|Short film\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2007\n|''Come to the Net''\n|Whitney\n|Short film\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" | 2007\n|''7\u201310 Split''\n|Whitney the Waitress\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2008\n|''[[Grizzly Park]]''\n|Tiffany Stone\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2008\n|''[[Made of Honor]]''\n|Stephanie\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=tvg/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2009\n|''Why Men Go Gay in L.A.''\n|Sarah\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2010\n|''In Fidelity''\n|Cindy\n| Short film\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2010\n|''Successful Alcoholics''\n|\n| Short film\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012\n|''[[3,2,1... Frankie Go Boom]]''\n|Claudia\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2015\n|''[[The Wedding Ringer]]''\n|Holly Munk\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2015\n|''[[The Ridiculous 6]]''\n|Susannah\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n|''[[Unforgettable (2017 film)|Unforgettable]]''\n|Ali\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=unf/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2017\n|''[[The Female Brain (film)|The Female Brain]]''\n|Julia Brizendine\n|Also writer and director\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=fb/>\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=